## 1.Create a comparison table listing at least 3 key differences between WAN and LAN, and give one real-world example of each from apps or services you use daily (for example, IRCTC, Instagram, or Zomato).

| Feature | LAN (Local Area Network) | WAN (Wide Area Network) |
|---|---|---|
| Geographic scope | Covers a small area — a room, building, or campus | Spans cities, countries, or continents |
| Speed | Very high (1 Gbps–10 Gbps typical) | Lower and variable (depends on ISP/leased lines) |
| Ownership | Privately owned and managed (your router, switches) | Often leased from telecom providers (Jio, Airtel, BSNL) |
| Latency | Very low (1–5 ms) | Higher (20–200 ms depending on distance) |
| Cost | Low setup cost | Expensive — leased lines, MPLS circuits, ISP contracts |

Real-world examples:
- LAN: When you open the Zomato app on your phone connected to your home Wi-Fi, your device is on a LAN. Your router assigns it a local IP (192.168.x.x) and the data travels over your local network to reach your router.
- WAN: After leaving your router, that same Zomato request travels over Jio/Airtel's WAN infrastructure — crossing cities and data centers — to reach Zomato's servers in Mumbai or Hyderabad. Similarly, IRCTC bookings from a station in Ahmedabad connect to the CRIS data center in Delhi via WAN links.

