## 3. What is MPLS? (Short Summary)

Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a high-performance data-carrying technique used by ISPs and enterprise networks to speed up and shape traffic flows. Instead of each router independently examining a packet's IP header and deciding the next hop (as in traditional IP routing), MPLS assigns a short label to each packet at the network's entry point (ingress router). Subsequent routers — called Label Switch Routers (LSRs) — forward packets purely based on that label, without re-reading the IP address, making decisions much faster. This pre-determined path is called a Label Switched Path (LSP). At the egress router, the label is removed and the packet is delivered normally. Compared to traditional IP routing — which is "hop-by-hop" and relies on longest-prefix matching at every router — MPLS offers faster forwarding, traffic engineering capabilities (you can explicitly control which path traffic takes), and the ability to implement Quality of Service (QoS) by assigning different labels to different traffic classes.

