## 4.Observe the pre-configured MPLS network in the provided Packet Tracer or GNS3 file, and note down two routing behaviors that are different from standard IP routing.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Look for how labels are used and how packets move between routers.</em>

Since no Packet Tracer or GNS3 file was uploaded, here are the two key behaviors you should look for and note when you open your lab file:

Behavior 1 — Label-based forwarding instead of IP lookup:
In standard IP routing, every router runs a longest-prefix match on the destination IP in its routing table. In MPLS, once you inspect the forwarding table (`show mpls forwarding-table` in Cisco IOS), you'll see that the LSR doesn't look at the IP at all — it swaps an incoming label (e.g., label 100) for an outgoing label (e.g., label 200) and pushes the packet out a specific interface. This is a label swap operation, and it happens in hardware, making it far faster than an IP lookup.

Behavior 2 — Pre-established Label Switched Paths (LSPs) bypass per-hop routing decisions:
When you `ping` or `traceroute` across the MPLS domain in Packet Tracer/GNS3, you'll notice that intermediate routers (P routers) do not appear in the IP routing table for that destination — yet packets arrive correctly. This is because the LSP is a tunnel: only the ingress and egress PE routers know the ultimate destination IP. The core P routers only see and act on labels, meaning the path is entirely predetermined by the label stack, not by dynamic IP routing at each hop.

