## 5. List three specific benefits MPLS offers over traditional routing for companies running high-traffic apps like YouTube or BookMyShow, and briefly explain how each benefit helps in real-world scenarios.

1. Traffic engineering and path control
Traditional IP routing sends packets along the "best" path as computed by algorithms like OSPF or BGP — but "best" usually just means shortest, not least congested. MPLS allows network engineers to explicitly define alternate paths (bypass tunnels) so that YouTube video streams, for example, never traverse an already-congested link even if it's technically the shortest route. For BookMyShow during IPL ticket sales, this means burst traffic can be rerouted around congested backbone links in real time, preventing packet loss and buffering.

2. Quality of Service (QoS) with traffic prioritization
MPLS labels can carry an Experimental (EXP) bits field (now called Traffic Class bits) that allows different packet types to be treated differently. A telecom provider serving YouTube can mark video streaming packets as high-priority and bulk data transfers as best-effort. Even under heavy load, video packets get forwarded first. Traditional IP routing treats all packets equally by default — differentiation requires complex per-hop policy configurations at every router, which is hard to manage at scale.

3. Fast reroute (FRR) and high availability
MPLS supports Fast Reroute, where a pre-computed backup LSP is instantly activated (in under 50 milliseconds) if a primary path fails — far faster than waiting for routing protocols like OSPF to reconverge (which can take seconds). For a platform like BookMyShow processing thousands of transactions per second, a 5-second routing reconvergence would cause visible errors and failed payments. With MPLS FRR, the failover is nearly invisible to end users.
